        <div type="letter">
            <div type="text">
                <opener>
                    <placeName><hi rend="print">Down, | Beckenham, Kent. | Railway Station | Orpington. S.E.R.</hi></placeName>
                    <date>Jan. 4. 1877</date>
                    <salute>Dear Romanes,</salute>
                </opener>
                <div type="transcription">
                     
                    <p>From what you say I will not send you a blank certificate but wait till I hear from you or see you.<ref target="#foot.f1"/> I will however bring up a blank certificate with me. If convenient, will you come &amp; lunch on Monday at 2 Bryanston St at 1 o’clock?<ref target="#foot.f2"/> &amp; you can bring the certificate or send it, which ever you like</p> 
                    <p> Yours very sincerely | Ch. Darwin</p> 
                </div>
            </div>

            
            
        </div>

        

        

        <div type="footnotes">
            <note xml:id="foot.f1">Romanes’s letter has not been found, but see the <ref target="./DCP-LETT-10765.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">letter from Charles and Francis Darwin to G. J. Romanes, 2 January [1877]</ref> and n. 2. The ‘Certificate of a candidate for election’ had to be filled in by Romanes and signed by CD and others supporting his election to the <ref target="../nameregs/nameregs_4110.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">Royal Society of London</ref>.</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f2">The Monday following 4 January 1877 was 8 January. The Darwins stayed in London at the home of their daughter and son-in-law, Henrietta Emma and <ref target="../nameregs/nameregs_2952.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">Richard Buckley Litchfield</ref>, from 6 to 15 January 1877 (CD’s ‘Journal’ (Appendix II)).</note>
        </div>        
            
